<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>COLUMN: U.S. harbors terrorists, too<BR>Source: U-WIRE <BR>Publication date: 0000-00-00<BR>Arrival time: 2002-06-26<P>OXFORD, Miss. -- It sickens me that in a country like ours, in this day and age, with the technological advances and availability of information we have, that people still believe the hyperbolic and otherwise inane propaganda spewed forth by our government. <BR>Our current conflagration against "The Axis of Evil" is a prime candidate for review. Granted, the attack on Sept. 11 was a horrible atrocity, and the first time a national territory has been attacked since the war of 1812. (Hawaii was a colony and not a national territory). But, when you tune into CNN, FOX or wherever you get your news from, they have added the proverbial cream and sugar to your coffee of news. <P>Now, you may like your coffee sweetened and lightened, but when it comes down to changing the story completely to shape foreign and internal perceptions of the United States and U.S. policy through lies and propaganda, the public mind no longer exists. Instead, it is replaced by an apathetic automaton that acquiesces to whatever it is told. This end is evident in the post Sept. 11 events, where the true designs of the government are shrouded in a cloak of deception while the media tells the ignorant public that we are fighting a legal and "JUST" war against a group of inherently evil countries known as the "Axis of Evil," whom are either harboring known international terrorists or support its use. <P>Our stance on this terrorism issue is a little comical and idiotic for two reasons. The first, is that the USA is widely regarded as a "leading terrorist state." That's right ladies and gentlemen, our government has committed numerous atrocities over the years; Nicaragua and Haiti are perfect examples of our heinous crimes. In the 1980s, the United States subjected Nicaragua to a brutal assault, killing tens of thousands of people. The international terrorist attack was followed by a horrible economic war, and being a small country, they were overwhelmed by us. Nicaragua could have done what America is doing now in Afghanistan and in the Middle East and waged an illegal war bombing innocent civilians and committing numerous terrorist attacks, but they decided to take their plight to the World Court. This legal course of action (which is what the United States was urged to follow against the Sept. 11 attack) ruled in favor of Nicaragua and forced the United States to pay reparations, where upon the United States dismissed the court's decision and escalated their attack. So, Nicaragua went to the Security Council and called the states to "observe international law," where upon the United States vetoed it (justice at work). <P>My second reason is that our government harbors international terrorists! The Cuban exiles in Miami are in fact probably the longest-lasting and most-prolific terrorist group in the world, and they're still at it. In the past year or so they've been busy bombing hotels in Havana, all directed from Miami. But our generosity toward terrorists doesn't stop with the Cubans; we also provide a safe haven for Guatemalans, Indonesians, Haitians, Salvadorians and countless other criminals guilty of international terrorism as long as they are friendly with U.S. foreign policy. <P>OK, in closing, I want to say that being in an institute for higher education as either a student or teacher should promote the spreading of ideas, knowledge and acceptance, not condone it or repress it. Challenge the institution, don't take the news for its face value and remember that there are two sides to every story. The other side is usually the truth, case in point: The United States is the only country in the world condemned by the world court for international terrorism and rejected a Security Council resolution to "observe international law." <P>I don't ever remember seeing that in the news, but it nonetheless happened and is documented. So, with that in mind, don't take the news as the gospel truth, it's not. Formulate your own opinions and look at both sides. <P>"Private capitalists inevitably control, directly or indirectly, the main sources of information. It is thus extremely difficult, and indeed in most cases quite impossible, for the individual citizen to come to objective conclusions and to make intelligent use of his political rights," -- Albert Einstein. <P>(C) 2002 Daily Mississippian via U-WIRE <BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I thought this was an interesting article, and the quote at the end by Einstein is one that I have both heard before and completely agree with.<P>This article will probably infuriate the "America is never wrong" crowd, but it gave me pause to think...<P>Does America have a policy of harboring terrorists, as long as those terrorists agree with the political interests of the country?  Is this right?<P>-incandescent-
</FONT>
