<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I have no illusions that the U.S. is some kind of perfect entity.<P>From what we know, some things are questionable. Leaves you to wonder about what we don't know. That would also be questionable.<P>But we do know that we were attacked on Sept. 11. We do know the organization that orchestrated the attack. We do know that a lot of our fellow Americans were killed in that attack.<P>Now, the U.S. may have had no business in the past with its dealings with insert_country_here, and perhaps the cumulative affect of those dealings contributed to the attack we faced on 9-1-1.<P>But as a regular Joe, if I'm getting beat on I'm far more likely to defend myself first and ask pressing, detailed questions later. Want to talk it out? Fine. But you start just beating on me and I will defend myself. Right or wrong.<P>If the terrorists want to talk, they could talk. But they don't. They want to fight. And they want to take their frustrations out on the civilians, rather than directly on the government(s) that is/are the focus of their hatred.<P>There is no good answer here. Hate always spurs hate. But to *not* defend ourselves is an invitation to get beat on some more. Remember the weakling kid in your 4th grade class who always got picked on? I do. And he kept getting picked on because he never defended himself.<P>In world politics, if you defend yourself, you can be criticized. Criticized for how you are defending yourself and how you are a hypocrite because of past actions and atrocities. But if you don't defend yourself, you will get beat on some more. And you will still be criticized.<P>There is no good answer. But the course of action the U.S. government has taken I support, because my life, and my family's life is at stake. I suppose that might be pretty short sighted. Perhaps it is. But do you want to die on an airplane? At a bus stop? In a mall? At the movies? Do you want to be in the middle of Washington DC or L.A. when a nuclear bomb goes off?<P>One of the best ways you can come to terms with how you truly feel about this whole crisis is to imagine your death being caused by it. And not because you are an armed soldier, but just by going about your normal routine. Imagine dying. Or imagine someone you care about being killed. <P>If you can imagine this well enough, you will achieve a level of clarity that will oftentimes differ from your academic, feeling safe, non-threatened, logical reasoning. It's a very different mindset for sure.<P>--------------------<P>Thanks for listening. I'm Pissed.
