<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Incandescent, you're close;<P>I didn't say that it is BEST to actually utilize force to forward our national interests - - frequently, that is not the best way. Often, however, it is the only way. And the ability to use force if desired is the only reason our national interests can even be expressed, much less moved forward.<P>Serving the best interests of the American People includes not forcing those of them wearing uniforms to die for stupid reasons... so, most times, peaceful negotiation and compromise are the best road.<P>But yes, when you get to the basic interactions of governments, might makes right, has always made right, and the only way an opposing viewpoint has ever successfully disputed the point has been to gather sufficient might to enforce their own opinions; thereby proving the point again.<P>If the Allies had not had the might to put down the Axis powers (and it was a near thing; if Hitler had played it smart and cozied up to the Russians, then turned on them later, he well could have won - - he was planning to do this to the Japanese eventually), the worldwide concept of "what's right" would certainly be different than it is today.<P>Anyone who has ever stood behind the phrase "violence never solves anything," simply has not read enough history.<P>Violence, and the threat of violent reprisal for non-compliance, is the only factor that has ever resolved anything.<P>It would be great if the world didn't work this way, but it does, and currently all the wishful thinking and all the efforts of the "great men of peace" have yet to come up with a workable alternative... because, so long as ONE PERSON remains that is willing to use violence to get what they want (be it a slice of pizza or world domination), the threat of overwhelming reprisal backed by violence will be the only thing to restrain them.<P>And it's necessary to be able to face this fact undismayed before any sense at all can be made of hisotry or politics.<P>The world would no doubt like America nd Americans so much more if we were, small, weak, and had no voice in how the world is run... but I think I would find it far less comfortable to live here under those circumstances.<P>Americans created this government (the first one in history whose stated purpose was the welfare of all its people regardless of class, by the way) and fought a violent and bloody war to get it, because their previous government was not looking out for their best interests. Might (and some luck) made right.<P>Living under the protective blanket of the potential violence of the superpower governments and their ability (still not perfected) to enforce peace by threat of overwhelming violence, the majority of people fail to even recognize what it is that protects them, and enables them to form and express their (often woefully uninformed and blindly self-interested) opinions in the first place.<P>If not for the US's military might, you and I would not even be able to have this conversation.<P>--------------------<P>Grunthos the Flatulent<BR>54th level Asgoth<BR>Poet of Kria
</FONT>
