<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
A couple of small factual corrections for the thread in general.<P>The bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki were not, contrary to the popular teachings of revisonist historians, the wanton targeting of civilians for the purpose of creating as much horror as possible.<P>Both cities were major war materiels manufacturing and shipping centers, and were the best military targets within reach of the bombers that would still leave sufficient Japanese military and civilian authorites alive that a surrender could be offered and enforced. remember, Japan was an Empire - - kill the Emperor, and who has the authority to end the resistance of the Japanese military and civilians?<P>Unless you plan on killing ALL of your enemies, the intent of war is to force capitulation.<P>It was necessary to drop two bombs to demonstrate that more than one could be built.. although, ironically, had the plan failed, we would have had real problems making any more.<P>Far more German civilians died in the massive conventional bombing of German industrial centers than did Japanese civilians in the course of the entire war, including both atomic bomb blasts. Why? The germans insisted on placing their military and industrial facilities within civilian centers, and the bombing technology of the day did not make it possible to hit just the military targets. To go on fighting the German military without cutting their supply base would have forced the conflict to go much longer, with much greater loss of life.<P>The main differences between military actions (that often cause civilian collateral casualities) and terrorist attacks, is that terrorist attacks uniformly are against undefended, civilian targets, do not use identifiable military personnel or equipment, and do not have a direct military goal, but instead have as their only goal the emotional impact of unanticipated violence.<P>The US military takes great pains to avoid civilian casualties whenever possible within the limits of military necessity and technology, never targets solely civilian targets, and ruthlessly enforces such rules among it's own ranks when violations are discovered. In fact, most of the casualties taken by US military forces in the last 30 years' conflicts and actions could have been easily avoided if we'd been willing to disregard civilian casualties. <P>Iraq could have been bombed back to the stone age with a miniscule portion of our military ability. Afganistan too. Likewise Somalia. Bosnia. And others.<P>The US military casualties taken in each of these engagements stem directly from our unwillingness to use the overwhelming military might at our disposal with disregard for civilian casualties.<P>--------------------<P>Grunthos the Flatulent<BR>54th level Asgoth<BR>Poet of Kria
</FONT>
