<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Where were the human interest groups, when Cambodian rebels were maiming, torturing, and killing their own people over a 10 year period, killing off eventually one third of their population? Where were the protests, saying "Stop cutting open pregnant women with bayonetts, and ripping their unborn children out in front of their families!" <BR>Answer: They had nothing to gain by protesting that. Their agenda could not be furthered in anyway. <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Whose foreign policy destabilized Cambodia to the point that the Khmer Rouge were allowed to run rampant?  The United States and its allies.  Lots of people protested but nothing could be done from our perspective since the US was reeling from its failed adventure in SE Asia and unable or unwilling to do anything about it.  At that point the methods we had to deal with these problems weren&#8217;t that strong.  Once the Khmer Rouge was ousted by the Vietnamese army the UN moved in and was able to help Cambodia stage fair elections (relatively speaking).  Unfortunately a coup a few years later screwed that up too.<BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>To break away from the thread for a bit, I'd just like to say that I grow tired of the number of posts, pointing fingers and saying "How dare America do this!", without offering a superior solution. Any weak mind can point a finger and say "You Suck", but real problem solving requires the formulation of a solution that can be applied to the controversy at hand, and get better results. I have yet to see any of those idea's here. So keep whining away about "America this, and America that..." if you want. But its not helping anything.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Criticism helps, believe it or not.  There should always be critics of the US government no matter the policy of the government or the bias of the critic.  We need both sides of the argument to produce fair results, in my opinion.  This is what democracy is all about. <BR>A nice solution to the &#8220;problem&#8221; in Nicaragua in the 80s would have been to back off and leave them alone.  <BR>A good solution now would be to increase foreign aid and decrease defense spending.  We don&#8217;t need to improve an army that can already kick anyone&#8217;s ass many times over.  Well executed foreign aid projects would go a long way towards reducing what Sshadow said about the weak resenting the strong, the poor resenting the rich as well as reducing the flow of immigration and refugees.  It&#8217;s money well spent.  Right now we spend less than 1 percent of the federal budget on foreign aid.  Why?  Nobody&#8217;s asking for a huge increase.  How about one percentage point?  Give the army one or two few less fighter jets.  No one will notice.
