<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Isn't it odd, though, Green, that the countries that resent us most are the same ones we have tried the hardest to aid. Or that have profited most from trade with us.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Which countries would those be?  I can name a few that have gotten a lot of money out of us; Germany, Israel, Egypt, Bangladesh&#8230;  I think you have a few in mind.  I do understand what you mean though at it&#8217;s valid to a point.  <P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Yes, I'm not sure that buckets of increased foreign aid from rich to poor countries is the answer to the world's problems, either.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Again (I have to say this Incandescent), not a very Christian thing to believe&#8230;  Oh well.  The US really started with the foreign aid push after WWII when Europe was in pieces.  WWII was partly caused by the outlandish terms of the Treaty of Versailles that ended WWI and that put Germany into poverty which caused political instability.  One good way of promoting political stability in a country is by developing that country.  The US spends almost nothing on foreign aid but the potential of this kind of investment is enormous.  Not only can it improve the politics of that country (and thereby reducing the chance of terrorism), here&#8217;s something for the capitalist pigs too: development paves the way for increased trade which means more money for us!  Can&#8217;t trade easily with a country that has little or no or backdated port capacity.  Harder to sell computer software to a country that has bad power and telecom infrastructure.  It&#8217;s a win-win situation.  I never said it would solve the world&#8217;s problems.
